<FlowDocument
        xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        xmlns:talex="http://schemas.talex-soft.com/2010/xaml/presentation"
        Tag="Matrices: use group of cells as a matrix in expression..."
        FontFamily="Segoe UI">
    
    <Paragraph>
        <Span FontWeight="Bold">PowerCalc</Span> uses the A1 reference style, which refers to columns with letters (A through IV by default, for a total of 256 columns) and refers to rows with numbers (1 through 256 by default). These letters and numbers are called row and column headings. To refer to a cell, enter the column letter followed by the row number. For example, B2 refers to the cell at the intersection of column B and row 2.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To refer to a group of cells (matrix) in expression you should refer to <Span FontWeight="Bold">top left</Span> cell than type <Span FontWeight="Bold">:</Span> and refer to <Span FontWeight="Bold">bottom right</Span> cell.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="17" Margin="0,15,0,0">
        Examples:
    </Paragraph>
    <List Padding="25,0" Margin="0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>A10 - the cell in column A and row 10</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>A10:E20 - the matrix in columns A through E and rows 10 through 20</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
</FlowDocument>